Regularization  

In the split string formulation given in  
  , we encountered a set of
infinite dimensional matrices  and vectors 
. These represent Bogoliubov transformations
between odd and even modes, with  appearing when the full string
is expanded in terms of cosine modes, and 
 appearing when the full string is expanded in terms of sine
modes. Such transformations are essential in the Moyal formulation since
they carry basic information about string theory. We note that, the Moyal
star product itself, which is applied independently for each mode, has no
specific information about string theory, and as such is a more general
structure.

In the analysis of the matter sector as well as the sine mode
expansion given so far, there appears an associativity anomaly in the matrix
algebra of these matrices. This originates from the infinite dimensionality
of these matrices. It produces ambiguities in computations in string field
theory. To have a well defined theory, it is mandatory to define a deformed,
unambiguous, associative algebra that preserves the basic matrix algebraic
structure of these matrices. Such a deformation contains a
parameter  that corresponds to the rank of the matrices. The original
definition of these matrices given above is reproduced by taking the limit 
 of this parameter. All computations in the open string
field theory are performed unambiguously with finite  and the correct
value in string theory is obtained at the end of the computation by taking
the limit . This is the basic strategy for practical
computations in the MSFT proposal.

The deformed set of matrices for  that have correctly reproduced
string theory was proposed in. Since an additional set of
matrices  have appeared in the
ghost sector we need to obtain their deformation consistently with the
matter sector. For that purpose, we start from the infinite dimensional
matrix  and vectors  defined in, 
 
